\par\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The animal was clearly following a scent trail, but Marcus wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t sure what the trail had been made by until it found the juvenile badger he had killed earlier. It snuffled around the corpse and growled when it seemed to catch a second scent, leaving Marcus with a big problem. It was almost certainly his scent the beast had found, as it was heading directly toward the tree he was currently in. Given the aggressively territorial nature of honey badgers, and their renown for climbing trees, he was unlikely to escape a fight. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Luckily, he was in a much better position overall than he had been during the earlier fight. He had a good line of sight on the badger, which had not yet seen him. He focused and conjured a mana spike, blasting it down at the approaching creature\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s head. Unlike the previous encounter with the juvenile, the angle was all wrong for a quick killing blow and he didn\u8217\'92t overcharge the bolt. The spikes did not penetrate deeply, exploding on impact against the badger\u8217\'92s thick skull. He rained down a series of the exploding spikes, eliciting  squeals, growls and barks from the creature as it rushed to the tree and began climbing. [Sadly for the badger, covering that much ground under an assault from a Magus who held the higher ground was too much to ask.] It was perhaps 6 meters below Marcus when he landed a final bolt which pierced through the thinner flesh of the badgers vulnerable neck and exploded, severing the spine. <!$Scr_Ps::0>}
