\par\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Seeing as there still appeared to be some hours before sunrise, Marcus turned his attention to imbuing his Mana Spikes and Mana Barrier with his elemental affinity. A barrier that damaged those that struck it and spikes of corrosive lightning seemed like excellent additions to his arsenal. Especially if the affinity made it easier for the spikes to penetrate enemy defenses.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It was a process of trial and error and wasted a lot of mana, but as the world began to lighten ever so slightly, Marcus found a technique that worked without losing the explosive aspect of his Mana Spikes. He could wrap the inner, explosive core in a thin shell of neutral mana and then wrap that shell with his corrosive lightning. The neutral mana kept the corrosive lightning from interacting with the explosive core so that the spike would hit its target, causing the corrosive lightning to attack its target and let the spike penetrate deeply. Then the neutral shell would shatter and the core would explode. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Similarly, he layered the outer face of his mana barrier with the corrosive lightning, with a small gap between it and the protective layer of the barrier that he filled with more of the extremely stable neutral mana. The corrosive lightning would damage anyone and anything that struck it, while the neutral mana would help stabilize the protective portion of the barrier and toughen it.  Which left him with a much more potent defense.<!$Scr_Ps::0>}
